sections.example:
Let's create a simple React component that changes the text when a button is clicked. First, we define a functional component called 'TextChanger'. Inside this component, we use the useState hook to create a state variable called 'text' initialized to 'Hello, World!'. We also define a function called 'changeText' that updates the 'text' state to 'Text Changed!'. In the return statement, we render a paragraph displaying the current text and a button. The button has an onClick event handler that calls 'changeText' when clicked. This way, when the user clicks the button, the text changes. Here's the code: 

function TextChanger() {
  const [text, setText] = useState('Hello, World!');
  const changeText = () => setText('Text Changed!');
  return (
    <div>
      <p>{text}</p>
      <button onClick={changeText}>Change Text</button>
    </div>
  );
}

Let's enhance our previous example by logging the synthetic event when the button is clicked. We will modify the 'changeText' function to accept an event parameter. Inside this function, we will log the event to the console and then change the text. The updated code looks like this: 

function TextChanger() {
  const [text, setText] = useState('Hello, World!');
  const changeText = (event) => {
    console.log(event);
    setText('Text Changed!');
  };
  return (
    <div>
      <p>{text}</p>
      <button onClick={changeText}>Change Text</button>
    </div>
  );
}

Now, when the button is clicked, the synthetic event object will be logged to the console, allowing you to see all the properties available to you.
